        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Interpreting the spread\n| Observation | Interpretation |\n|---|---|\n| β values increase with higher chloride stoichiometry | This is consistent with progressive formation of Cd–chloride complexes in chloride-rich solutions |\n| Values vary with ionic strength | The spread likely reflects **conditional constants** measured under different ionic-strength/media conditions, so extremes should not be compared as if they were identical standard-state constants |\n| Data are all near room temperature | Temperature effects are not the main driver here; **medium/ionic strength** is the dominant source of variation in the retrieved log K set |\n\nSo, in short: **7 distinct literature sources** in SRD-46 report Cd²⁺–chloride stability constants, with **log K** values spanning **1.35–1.98** for CdCl⁺, **1.70–2.60** for CdCl₂(aq), and **1.50–2.80** for CdCl₃⁻, all essentially at **25 °C** over **0–4 M ionic strength**.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46.*",
